 the Discourse Relating to “Corrective Agents” for Black Males -- tResponse to Chapter 7 Black Role Models and Mentorship under Racial Capitalism -- t8 “Up to No Good”: Black on the Streets and Encountering Police -- tResponse to Chapter 8 It Could Have Been Written Today: A Montrealer’s Reflection -- t9 “Colour Matters”: Suburban Life as Social Mobility and Its High Cost for Black Youth -- tResponse to Chapter 9 “What Floats in the Air Is Chance”: Respectability Politics and the Search for Upward Mobility in Canada -- t10 Towards Equity in Education for Black Students in the Greater Toronto Area -- tResponse to Chapter 10 “I Will Treat All My Students with Respect”: The Limits of Good Intentions -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on research conducted in Black communities, along with over thirty years of teaching experience, Colour Matters presents a collection of essays that engages educators, youth workers, and policymakers to think about the ways in which race shapes the education, aspirations, and achievements of Black Canadians. Informed by the current socio-political Canadian landscape, Colour Matters covers topics relating to the lives of Black youth, with particular, though not exclusive, attention to young Black men in the Greater Toronto Area. The essays reflect the issues and concerns of the past thirty years, and question what has changed and what has remained the same. Each essay is accompanied by an insightful response from a scholar engaging with topics such as immigration, schooling, athletics, mentorship, and police surveillance. With the perspectives of scholars from the United Kingdom, the United States, and Canada, Colour Matters provides provocative narratives of Black experiences that alert us to what more might be said, or said differently, about the social, cultural, educational, political, and occupational worlds of Black youth in Canada. This book probes the ongoing need to understand, in nuanced and complex ways, the marginalization and racialization of Black youth in a time of growing demands for a societal response to anti-Black racism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBlack peoplexEducationzOntariozToronto. 0aBlack peoplezOntariozTorontoxSocial conditions. 0aBlack peoplezOntariozTorontoxSocial life and customs. 0aBlack peoplezOntariozToronto. 0aEthnic relations. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aBlack Canadian youth experiences.  aanti-racism.  acareer trajectories of Black students.  aeducation of Black students.  aeducation.  alongitudinal research of Black youth.  amasculinity.  arace.1 aAladejebi, Funké, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackett, Adelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Mark V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGooden, Amoaba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenry, Annette M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Michele A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Joyce E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTate, Shirley Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Leanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTecle, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTrotz, D. Alissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://